definitions.definition: perform (an action, the precise nature of which is often unspecified).
examples: something must be done about the city's traffic
synonyms: engineer; informalpull off; formaleffectuate "she does most of the manual work"

examples: Dad always did the cooking on Sundays

definitions.definition: work on (something) to bring it to completion or to a required state.
examples: it takes them longer to do their hair than me
synonyms: be in charge of; Moreinformalfix "the boys will do the dinner"style
cut; informalfix "the maid did her hair"

definitions.definition: make or have available and provide.
examples: he's doing bistro food
synonyms: sketch; informalknock off "the company is doing a new range of footwear"

examples: Joe was doing sums aloud
synonyms: resolve "show me how to do these equations"

definitions.definition: cook (food) to completion or to a specified degree.
examples: if a knife inserted into the center comes out clean, then your pie is done

definitions.definition: (often in questions) work at for a living.
examples: what does she do?
synonyms: earn a living at "what does he do?"

definitions.definition: produce or give a performance of (a particular play, opera, etc.).
examples: the Royal Shakespeare Company is doing Macbeth next month
synonyms: participate in "I am doing a show to raise money"

definitions.definition: perform (a particular role, song, etc.) or imitate (a particular person) in order to entertain people.
examples: he not only does Schwarzenegger and Groucho, he becomes them
he doesn't smoke, drink, or do drugs
the barber said he'd do me next
one car I looked at had done 112,000 miles
synonyms: log; informalchalk up "the cyclists do 30 kilometers per day"

examples: I was speeding, doing seventy-five
synonyms: move at "he was doing 25 mph over the speed limit"

examples: last time I did New York–Philadelphia round trip by train it was over 80 bucks
our bestselling album did about a million worldwide

definitions.definition: visit as a tourist, especially in a superficial or hurried way.
examples: the tourists are allotted only a day to “do” Verona
synonyms: sightsee in "we're doing Scotland this summer"

definitions.definition: spend (a specified period of time), typically in prison or in a particular occupation.
examples: he did five years for manslaughter
you must sit there and wait till I'm done
the special formula continues to beautify your tan when the day is done

definitions.definition: give up concern for: have finished with.
examples: I would sell the place and have done with it
synonyms: want no more to do with "she was done with him"

definitions.definition: act or behave in a specified way.
examples: they are free to do as they please
synonyms: acquit oneself; formalcomport oneself "they can do as they please"

definitions.definition: make progress or perform in a specified way; get on.
examples: when a team is doing badly, it's not easy for a new player to settle in
synonyms: prosper "he is doing well at college"

examples: the walk will do me good
the years of stagnation did a lot of harm to the younger generation
if he's anything like you, he'll do
synonyms: meet one's needs "regular coffee will do"

examples: he was the guy who did Maranzano
once you falter, you're done
this would be an easy place to do, and there was plenty of money lying around
in business you had to do your competitors before they did you
we got done for conspiracy to commit murder

definitions.definition: used before a verb (except be, can, may, ought, shall, will ) in questions and negative statements.
examples: do you have any pets?
you write poetry, don't you?
don't be silly

definitions.definition: used to refer to a verb already mentioned.
examples: he looks better than he did before

definitions.definition: used to give emphasis to a positive verb.
examples: I do want to act on this

definitions.definition: used in positive commands to give polite encouragement.
examples: do tell me!

definitions.definition: used with inversion of a subject and verb when an adverbial phrase begins a clause for emphasis.
examples: only rarely did they succumb
